###use hold_out method to divide the data set into train set and test set

set.seed(1235)
train_id<-sample(1:nrow(df_all),size=floor(0.9*nrow(df_all)))
df_all_train<-df_all %>%slice(train_id)
df_all_test<-df_all %>%slice(-train_id)

##overview of part_iii_classification_D

The aim of this part is training,evaluating, tuning and comparing simple to complex models via resampling.
You must train and tune the following models:
1.generalized linear models:
1) all categorical and continuous inputs-linear additvie features
2) all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs, include additive categorical features
3) The 2 models selected from iiiA
2.regularized logistic regression with elastic net
1) all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs, include additive categorical features
2) the more complex of the models selected from iiA
3.neural network
4.random forest
5.gradient boosted tree
6.2 methods of your choice that we did not explicitly discuss in lecture
7.you must decide the resampling scheme, what kind of preprocessing options you should consider
8.you must identify the best model
9.which model is the best if you are interested in maximizing Accuracy compared to maximizing the area under the ROC Curve?

my_ctrl <- trainControl(method = 'repeatedcv', number = 5, repeats = 3,
                            summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
                            classProbs = TRUE,
                            savePredictions = TRUE)

my_metric<- "ROC"

generalized linear models:

all categorical and continuous inputs-linear additive features

c_fit_glm_all_inputs<-train(outcome ~ .,
                   data = df_all_train,
                   method = "glm",
                   metric = my_metric,
                   preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                   trControl = my_ctrl)

c_fit_glm_all_inputs %>%readr::write_rds('c_fit_glm_all_inputs.rds')

all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs, include additive categorical features

c_fit_glm_all_pairwise<-train(outcome ~ (.)^2,
                   data = df_all_train,
                   method = "glm",
                   metric = my_metric,
                   preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                   trControl = my_ctrl)

## ROC was used to select the optimal model using the largest value.
## The final values used for the model were alpha = 1 and lambda = 0.03427453.
my_lambda_grid<- exp(seq(log(min(c_fit_glmnet_pairwise$results$lambda)),
                                    log(max(c_fit_glmnet_pairwise$results$lambda)),
                                    length.out = 25)) 
fit_glmnet_grid <- expand.grid(alpha = seq(0.1, 0.9, by = 0.1),
                                      lambda = my_lambda_grid)
c_fit_glmnet_pairwise_tune<-train(outcome~(.)^2,
                           data=df_all_train,
                           method = "glmnet",
                            metric = my_metric,
                            preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                           tuneGrid=fit_glmnet_grid,
                            trControl = my_ctrl)

                preProcess = c("center", "scale","pca"),

my_lambda_grid<- exp(seq(log(min(c_fit_glmnet_3$results$lambda)),
                                    log(max(c_fit_glmnet_3$results$lambda)),
                                    length.out = 25))
fit_glmnet_grid <- expand.grid(alpha = seq(0.1, 0.9, by = 0.1),
                                      lambda = my_lambda_grid)
c_fit_glmnet_3_tune<-train(outcome~.,
                data=df_all_train,
                method = "glmnet",
                metric = my_metric,
                preProcess = c("center", "scale","pca"),
                tuneGrid=fit_glmnet_grid,
                trControl = my_ctrl)

my_lambda_grid<- exp(seq(log(min(c_fit_glmnet_2$results$lambda)),
                                    log(max(c_fit_glmnet_2$results$lambda)),
                                    length.out = 25))
fit_glmnet_grid <- expand.grid(alpha = seq(0.1, 0.9, by = 0.1),
                                      lambda = my_lambda_grid)

                trControl = my_ctrl)

c_fit_nnet_additive <- train(outcome ~ .,
                   data = df_all_train,
                   method = "nnet",
                   metric = my_metric,
                   preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                   trControl = my_ctrl,
                   trace = FALSE)

                   data = df_all_train,
                   method = "pcaNNet",
                   metric = my_metric,

                   trControl = my_ctrl,
                   tuneGrid=nnet_grid,
                   trace = FALSE)

                   importance = TRUE)

## The final value used for the model was mtry = 2.
rf_grid <- expand.grid(.mtry=sqrt(ncol(df_all[,2])))
c_fit_rf_additive_tune <- train(outcome ~ .,
                   data = df_all_train,
                   method = "rf",
                   metric = my_metric,
                   trControl = my_ctrl,
                   tuneGrid=rf_grid,
                   importance = TRUE)

c_fit_xgb_additive_tune <- train(outcome~.,
                               data=df_all_train,
                               method = "xgbTree",
                              metric = my_metric,
                               trControl = my_ctrl,
                              tuneGrid=xgbGrid,
                              preProcess=c('center','scale','pca')
                               )

identify the best model

c_fit_glm_all_inputs<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_glm_all_inputs.rds")
c_fit_glm_all_pairwise<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_glm_all_pairwise.rds")
c_fit_glm_8<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_glm_8.rds")
c_fit_glm_2<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_glm_2.rds")
c_fit_glmnet_pairwise_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_glmnet_pairwise_tune.rds")
c_fit_glmnet_3_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_glmnet_3_tune.rds")
c_fit_glmnet_2_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_glmnet_2_tune.rds")
c_fit_nnet_additive_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_nnet_additive_tune.rds")
c_fit_rf_additive_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_rf_additive_tune.rds")
c_fit_xgb_additive_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_xgb_additive_tune.rds")
c_fit_svm_additive_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_svm_additive_tune.rds")
c_fit_adaboost_additive_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_fit_adaboost_additive_tune.rds")
c_pca_nnet_additive_tune<-readr::read_rds("c_pca_nnet_additive_tune.rds")
results<-resamples(list(mod_1=c_fit_glm_all_inputs,
                        mod_2=c_fit_glm_all_pairwise,
                        mod_3=c_fit_glm_8,
                        mod_4=c_fit_glm_2,
                        mod_5=c_fit_glmnet_pairwise_tune,
                        mod_6=c_fit_glmnet_3_tune,
                        mod_7=c_fit_glmnet_2_tune,
                        mod_8=c_fit_nnet_additive_tune,
                        mod_9=c_fit_rf_additive_tune,
                        mod_10=c_fit_xgb_additive_tune,
                        mod_11=c_fit_svm_additive_tune,
                        mod_12=c_fit_adaboost_additive_tune,
                        mod_13=c_pca_nnet_additive_tune))
dotplot(results,metric="ROC")

Based on the result, the ROC of mod_5,mod_6,mod_13 and mod_8 are the highest, considering the confidence interval mod_13 is the best one.
However, to prevent the model to be too overfitting, I choose the hold set to do the prediction again and calculate the value of ROC again.

library(caTools)
result_1<-predict(c_fit_glm_all_inputs,df_all_test,type='prob')

Based on the ROC plot, we can also find out that the model 5-c_fit_glmnet_pairwise_tune is overfitting, so the best model is model_13,c_pca_nnet_additive_tune.

##which model is the best if you are interested in maximizing Accuracy compared to maximizing the area under the ROC Curve?
Based on the results above, model1-c_fit_glm_all_inputs(general linear model with all inputs) is the best model.

result_1<-predict(c_fit_glm_all_inputs,df_all_test,thresholder=0.5)
result_2<-predict(c_fit_glm_all_pairwise,df_all_test,thresholder=0.5)
## Warning in predict.lm(object, newdata, se.fit, scale = 1, type = if (type == :

results_acc<-c(r1=sum(ifelse(result_1==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r2=sum(ifelse(result_2==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r3=sum(ifelse(result_3==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r4=sum(ifelse(result_4==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r5=sum(ifelse(result_5==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r6=sum(ifelse(result_6==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r7=sum(ifelse(result_7==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r8=sum(ifelse(result_8==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r9=sum(ifelse(result_9==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r10=sum(ifelse(result_10==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r11=sum(ifelse(result_11==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r12=sum(ifelse(result_12==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1),
               r13=sum(ifelse(result_13==df_all_test$outcome,1,0))/length(result_1))
results_acc %>%dotplot()

Based on the results above, model1-c_fit_glm_all_inputs(general linear model with all inputs) and model11-c_fit_svm_additive_tune are the best model, which hav high but not the highest ROC.
This is because the data we are working on is very close to imbalanced( the probability of event is only 0.18, which is close to the line of 0.15 to be imbalanced), so some model prefers to classify the data to be non_event to increase the value of accuracy.
